Reduced surface energy means excellent adhesion on common plastic substrates such as PET, which greatly expands the application range of bio-based inks. Surface energy and printing firmness were further analyzed according to hydrophobicity. WCA was measured for GP films and printed patterns respectively (Table 3
                        ). The contact angle was 104.8° for GA film, and reduced to 55.3° after 30 wt% of F-WPU was added. The value of WCA was opposite to the expected result based on the hydrophilicity of GA and the hydrophilicity of F-WPU, which is attributed to the change in surface roughness. F-WPU will reduce the crystallinity of the film and make the surface rougher, which is evidence of the existence of the dual network system. WCA increased significantly after the addition of F-CDs. Combined with the results of XRD, the increase in hydrophobicity is attributed to the adjustment of crystallinity by F-CDs. Since the surface roughness of printing patterns was not affected by crystallinity, the hydrophobic effect of F-WPU and F-CDs is more obvious. The WAC of GP3-0 printed pattern was 13.34° higher than that of GA, and continues to increase to 89.8° with the introduction of F-CDs (Fig. 5
                        b). The increase was attributed to the fluorine-containing branches on F-WPU and the hydrophobic functional groups on the surface of F-CDs. Compared with other hydrophobic nanoparticles, the WCA contributed by 2.0 wt% F-CDs is similar to that of 30 wt% methyltrimethoxysilane treated SiO2 (Smitha et al., 2007).

With an average thickness of 0.12 mm, GP films were light yellow under sunlight and had extremely high transparency (Fig. 9
                        a). At 600 nm the transparency value is 0.34 for GA and GP3-0 films, and from 0.38 to 0.62 ranged for GP films (Table 4
                        ). Under 360 nm UV excitation, composite films with different components could all emit fluorescence (Fig. 9c). This is because GA itself has aggregation-induced emission (AIE) effect and can emit blue fluorescence (Xu et al., 2021). The concentration of gelatin decreased after F-WPU was added, which reduced the fluorescence intensity of liquid dispersion (Fig. 9b). The fluorescence of composite films became bright blue-green after introducing F-CDs and reaches maximum around 0.5 wt%, which was much higher than the concentration with the strongest fluorescence in ethanol solution.
